// Moldovan Cyrillic (ro-Cyrl-MD) — designed layout; no OS source exists.
//
// xkb `md` is the Romanian *Latin* layout (plus Gagauz); Windows never
// shipped a Moldovan Cyrillic KLID (kbdlayout.info lists only the three
// Romanian Latin layouts under 0418); CLDR has no osx keylayout. This
// file reconstructs the layout the way Soviet-era Moldavian SSR keyboards
// worked: the Russian ЙЦУКЕН base with the standard-orthography deviations.
//
// The Moldovan Cyrillic alphabet (31 letters, per the 1957 MSSR decree
// dropping щ/ъ and the 1967 decree adding ӂ; still official in
// Transnistria): а б в г д е ж ӂ з и й к л м н о п р с т у ф х ц ч ш
// ы ь э ю я. Relative to Russian it lacks ё, щ, ъ and adds ӂ (U+04C2,
// zhe with breve — Romanian ge/gi, [d͡ʒ]).
//
// ӂ placement — the freed щ key (AD09):
//   * Dropping щ and ъ frees exactly two letter keys of the Russian base;
//     the historically attested choices for the one extra letter are the
//     щ and ъ positions.
//   * Belarusian is the structurally identical precedent — a Cyrillic
//     orthography that likewise lacks щ and gained one extra full-frequency
//     letter (ў) — and its default national layout (xkb `by`, Windows KLID
//     00000423) puts that letter on the Russian щ position, AD09.
//   * Frequency agrees: ӂ carries every Romanian ge/gi (мерӂе, фуӂе,
//     ӂенерал …), so it belongs on a main-block key, not the peripheral
//     AD12 ъ key — the key Soviet typewriter keyboards frequently omitted
//     altogether.
//
// щ moves to AltGr on the same key, and ё (TLDE) and ъ (AD12) keep their
// Russian positions: all three letters are admitted in Russian loanwords
// and proper names, so they stay reachable without costing ӂ its key.

default partial alphanumeric_keys
xkb_symbols "basic" {

    include "ru(winkeys)"
    name[Group1]="Moldavian (Cyrillic)";

    key <AD09> { [ U04C2, U04C1, Cyrillic_shcha, Cyrillic_SHCHA ] };  // ӂ Ӂ щ Щ

    include "level3(ralt_switch)"
};
